    <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <para id="para-00001"><emphasis effect="bold">After completing this section, you should be able to:</emphasis></para>
    <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00001">
    <item>Read the time on an analog clock.</item>
    <item>Express time in standard time or military time.</item>
    </list>
    </section>
    <para id="para-00002">Have you ever wondered why anyone still uses traditional analog clocks at all, now that we have digital clocks that are so much easier to read? Apart from the decorative ambience of a beautiful analog clock, there are some practical considerations. Analog clocks are less expensive to purchase and more energy efficient, often running for years on few small batteries. Mathematicians appreciate analog clocks for a different reason. They are a visual representation of a special kind of number system in which crazy things happen. For example, suppose the current time is 6 o’clock. What time will it be in 7 hours? If you said, 1 o’clock, you are correct! So, 6 o’clock plus 7 hours is 1 o’clock, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math>!</para>
    <section id="sect-00002" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
    <title>The Face of a Clock</title>
    <para id="para-00003">Let’s look at the parts of the face of an analog clock as shown in <link target-id="fig-00002" document="m00039">Figure A.2</link>. The face of a clock is generally circular with the circle divided into 12 equal parts, one for each hour. The numbers 1 through 12 are displayed with 12 at the top, 6 at the bottom, 3 on the right, and 9 on the left. There are up to 3 pointers attached at the center of the clock that rotate at different speeds. These are called the <emphasis effect="bold">hands</emphasis> of the clock. Each hand takes a different amount of time to make a full rotation. The rotation is always in the same direction as the numbers are increasing 1, 2, 3, …. This direction is known as <emphasis effect="bold">clockwise</emphasis>. The opposite direction, 12, 11, 10, … is known as <emphasis effect="bold">counterclockwise</emphasis>.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Photo_CRA_02_003-5.png"/>
    </media>	
    <caption>Face of Analog Clock (credit: XX)</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">Think of the 12 as the starting position. The hour hand is the shortest of the three and the slowest moving. It takes 12 hours for the hour hand to make a complete rotation around the circle. The minute hand is longer and moves much faster. The minute hand takes 1 hour to make a complete rotation. The second hand is also long, but usually more narrow and differs from the other two by color or shape or both. The second hand makes a complete rotation very quickly, in only 1 minute! It is very common for clocks to have only the hour and minute hands.</para>
    <example id="exam-00001">
    <title>Determining How Much Time Has Passed</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00001">
    <problem id="prob-00001">
    <para id="para-00005">How much time has passed in each scenario?</para>
    <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00002">
    <item>The hour hand to move from the 2 to the 7.</item>
    <item>The second hand moved from the 11 to the 12.</item>
    <item>The minute hand moved from 4 to 7.</item>
    </list>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00001">
    <para id="para-00006"><list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00003">
    <item>One rotation around the circle is 12 hours for the hour hand. Since the circle is divided into 12 parts, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>12</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>hours</mtext><mo>÷</mo><mn>12</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>parts</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math> hour for each part. To move from the 2 to the 7, the hour hand most pass through <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></math> parts which will take 5 hours.</item>
    <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">One rotation around the circle is 1 minute or 60 seconds for the second hand. Since the circle is divided into 12 parts, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>60</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>seconds</mtext><mo>÷</mo><mn>12</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>parts</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></math> seconds for each part. To move from the 11 to the 12, the second hand must pass through 1 part which means that 5 seconds have past.</item>
    <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">One rotation around the circle is 1 hour or 60 minutes for the minute hand. Since the circle is divided into 12 parts, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>60</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>minutes</mtext><mo>÷</mo><mn>12</mn><mspace width="0.28em"/><mtext>parts</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></math> minutes for each part. To move from the 4 to the 7, the minute hand passes through <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></math> parts, which is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></math> minutes.</item>
    </list></para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
