    <section id="sect-00003">
    <title>Telling Time</title>
    <para id="para-00008">When we read the time off a clock, we call it “telling time.” To tell time, we read the hours, then minutes, then seconds (if appropriate), beginning with the largest unit of time and working down to the smallest.</para>
    <para id="para-00009">The clock face in <link target-id="fig-00002" document="m00039">Figure A.2</link> displays the time 12:30 and 17 seconds. To see this, begin by identifying the value of the hour hand, which is the shorter of the two black hands. Notice that it has moved past the 12, but hasn’t quite reached the 1. This means that the hour is 12. Next, we look at the minute hand. Since the minute hand moves around the clock once an hour and there are 60 minutes in an hour, each of the 12 parts of the circle must represent <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>÷</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></math> minutes. This is shown in <link target-id="fig-00003" document="m00039">Figure A.3</link>.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00003" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_image_A_02_001.png"/>
    </media>
    <caption>Face of Clock Divided into 60 Equal Parts</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00010">It is often the case that the minutes are not marked off on the clock, and skip counting by fives will help you read the minutes. In this case, the minute hand is pointing toward 6 and 6 fives is 30. So far, we know that the clock reads 12:30. Notice that we put a colon between the hours and the minutes. If we want to read the second hand too, remember that the second hand goes around the clock once per minute which means once every 60 seconds. So, the same division of the circle into 60 equal pieces from <link target-id="fig-00003" document="m00039">Figure A.3</link> will work for seconds. In the case of the clock in <link target-id="fig-00003" document="m00039">Figure A.3</link>, the second hand is pointing two marks past 15, which is 17 seconds. So, the time on this clock is 12:30 and 17 seconds, or 12:30:17, in HH:MM:SS (Hour Hour: Minute Minute: Second Second) format. Either way, this is read allowed as “12 thirty and 17 seconds.” The seconds are often not given. When the minutes are 0, the time is read as the hour followed by “o’clock”. For example, 10:00, is read 10 o’clock.</para>
    <example id="exam-00002">
    <title>Determining What Time Someone Left for Work</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00003">
    <problem id="prob-00003">
    <para id="para-00011">One of the clocks in <link target-id="fig-00004" document="m00039">Figure A.4</link> shows the time that Leandro left for work today. If he always leaves between 5 o’clock and 9 o’clock in the morning, which clock shows the time he left for work?</para>
    <figure id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Photo_CRA_02_006-8.png"/>
    </media>
    <caption>Clocks A, B and C</caption>
    </figure>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00002">
    <para id="para-00012"><emphasis effect="bold">Clock A:</emphasis> The hour hand has passed 7 but it has not reached 8; so, the hour is 7. The minute hand is one mark past 7. Since <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>7</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>35</mn></mrow></math> minutes, one mark past 7 is 36 minutes. The second hand is on the 12, which represents 0 seconds. So, the time is 7:36:00. When the hour is only one digit, we don’t usually write a leading zero. So, we won’t write 07:36:00, although that is also correct.</para>
    <para id="para-00013" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="bold">Clock B:</emphasis> The hour hand has passed the 2 but it has not reached the 3; so, the hour is 2. The minute hand is a little more than three marks past 9. Since <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></math> minutes, 3 marks past the 9 is 48 minutes. The second hand is four marks past the 5. Since <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></math> seconds, four marks past 5 is 29 seconds. So, the time is 2:45:25.</para>
    <para id="para-00014" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="bold">Clock C:</emphasis> The hour hand is pointing directly at 11; so, the hour is 11. The minute hand is pointing directly at 12 which indicates 0 minutes. The second hand is two marks past the 12. Since 12 is 0 seconds, two marks past 12 is 2 seconds. So, the time is 11:00:02.</para>
    <para id="para-00015">The only time that is between 5 o’clock and 9 o’clock is 7:36:00. So, Leandro left at 7:36 exactly.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
