    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Standard Time</title>
    <para id="para-00017">Since there are 24 hours in a day, the hour hand of a clock must make two full rotations each day. As you know, this means there are two different “7 o’clocks” each day which can get confusing. In Latin, <emphasis effect="bold">meridiem</emphasis> means midday, also known as noon. So, we distinguish between the two different 7 o’clocks, one that is <emphasis effect="bold">ante meridiem (AM)</emphasis>, before midday, and one that is <emphasis effect="bold">post meridiem (PM)</emphasis>, after midday. There is usually no indication of AM or PM on analog clocks and we have to determine which from context. This system is known as <emphasis effect="bold">standard time</emphasis> or sometimes called <emphasis effect="bold">civilian time</emphasis>. In standard time, <emphasis effect="bold">noon</emphasis> is 12 PM and <emphasis effect="bold">midnight</emphasis> is 12 AM.</para>
    <example id="exam-00003">
    <title>Determining What Time Friends Are Eating Dinner</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00005">
    <problem id="prob-00005">
    <para id="para-00018">Jean is meeting his friend at a restaurant to eat dinner after work at the time indicated on the clock in <link target-id="fig-00005" document="m00039">Figure A.6</link>. Give the time in standard time.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Photo_CRA_02_011.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>Dinner Time</caption>
    </figure>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00003">
    <para id="para-00019">Since the hour hand is past 7 but hasn’t reached 8, the hour is 7. The minute hand is on the 9 indicates <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></math> minutes. Since Jean is eating dinner after work, it is past midday, which is PM. So, the standard time is 7:45 PM.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
