    <section id="sect-00005">
    <title>Military Time</title>
    <para id="para-00021">An alternative to standard time, is to number the hours of the day from 0 to 24, where the AM hours before midday are numbered 0 through 11 and the PM hours after midday are numbered 12 through 24. In this system, known as <emphasis effect="bold">military time</emphasis>, a colon is not used. For example, the time 11:00 AM is written 1100 and read aloud as “eleven hundred hours,” and the time 7:30 am is written 0730 and read aloud as “O seven hundred thirty hours.” Noon is represented as 1200. Any time past midday can be found by adding 1200 to the time. For example, the time 1:15 pm is an hour and 15 minutes past midday. Midday is 1200 hours, so 1 hour and 15 minutes later is .. hours. Midnight, can be represented in two ways, as 000, read “zero hundred hours,” or as 2400, read as “twenty four hundred hours.” The convention is to use 000 when talking about the time an event begins, or 2400 when referring to the time an event ends.</para>
    <example id="exam-00004">
    <title>Converting Between Standard and Military Times</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00007">
    <problem id="prob-00007">
    <para id="para-00022">Repeat <link target-id="exer-00005" document="m00039">Example A.3</link>, except give the answer in military time.</para>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00004">
    <para id="para-00023">7:45 PM is past midday; so, add 1200 to 745 to get 1945.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
